Date: 15/1/1947
Source: NZ Observer
Author:
Vol / Page: 9
Edition:
Quote: Down below.. is the solitary block. This is the dreaded "dummy" where the prison J.P. sends recalcitrants for a spell on bread and water.
Notes:

Date: 31/7/1917
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 8
Edition:
Quote: He [sc. Paddy Webb] described the punishment known as "dummy" - solitary confinement in a dark cell on hard rations. He had seen men go into "dummy" in fairly good health and come out physical wrecks. In "dummy" they got three small blankets, and had to sleep on the floor.
Notes:

Date: 14/8/1917
Source: Wanganui Herald
Author:
Vol / Page: 4
Edition:
Quote: Mr Webb added that if he had been found out in this dishonest behaviour, he would have been put in the 'dummy' - solitary confinement.
Notes:

Date: 5/6/1909
Source: NZ Truth
Author:
Vol / Page: 206/5/5
Edition:
Quote: The young prisoner [in the Terrace Gaol] got so bad with boils that he was unable to work, and was placed in `The Dummy,' a building which the prisoner described to `Truth' as an old chicken house. Whilst in `The Dummy' he received no attention whatever, except that his meals were brought to him.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1936
Source: Passport to Hell
Author: HYDE
Vol / Page: 62
Edition:
Quote: He was taken before the Governor and sentenced to three days in the Dummy. It is always dusk in the Dummy, which lies underground. ... At six in the morning the door is unlocked, and the prisoner gets his clothes, all except boots.
